-- Oil Options Volatility Rises as Futures Advance a Second Day
-- B y   B a r b a r a   P o w e l l
-- 2013-05-16T19:49:53Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-05-16/oil-options-volatility-rises-as-futures-advance-a-second-day.html
Crude oil options volatility rose as
the underlying futures advanced for a second straight session.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
July, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a gauge
of options prices, was 21.97 percent at 3:10 p.m. on the  New
York Mercantile Exchange , up from 21.31 percent yesterday.  West Texas Intermediate crude for June delivery advanced 86
cents to settle at $95.16 a barrel a barrel on the Nymex. July-delivery WTI increased 89 cents to $95.45.  The most-active options in electronic trading today were
July $75 puts, which were unchanged at 5 cents a barrel on
volume of 4,645 contracts at 3:48 p.m. in  New York . June $90
calls were the second-most active, falling 8 cents to 91 cents
on 3,644 lots.  Puts accounted for 53 percent of electronic trading volume
today and made up 51 percent of the of the prior trading dayâ€™s
volume of 213,866 contracts.  June $95 calls were the most-active options traded in the
previous session, with 8,975 contracts changing hands. They fell
16 cents to 27 cents a barrel. June $90 puts declined 4 cents to
3 cents a barrel on 8,787 lots.  Open interest was highest for December $105 calls with
37,770 contracts. Next were June $80 puts with 37,664 lots and
December $110 calls with 33,926.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information the next business day on open-outcry volume, where the bulk of options activity occurs.  To contact the reporter on this story:
